    {
        "content": "<p>Why do we create C wrappers to C code in <a href=\"https://github.com/torvalds/linux/tree/master/rust/helpers\">rust/helpers</a> instead of using the original C code directly?</p>",
        "id": 531143580,
        "sender_full_name": "Nika Krasnova",
        "timestamp": 1753624209
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because these C APIs defined as macro, or static inline function</p>",
        "id": 531144199,
        "sender_full_name": "JCKeep",
        "timestamp": 1753624460
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, yea, makes sense. Thx!</p>",
        "id": 531144688,
        "sender_full_name": "Nika Krasnova",
        "timestamp": 1753624648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"939493\">Nikita Krasnov</span> has marked this topic as resolved.</p>",
        "id": 531144831,
        "sender_full_name": "Notification Bot",
        "timestamp": 1753624699
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The top of the file explains it :)</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"C\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"cm\">/*</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> * Non-trivial C macros cannot be used in Rust. Similarly, inlined C functions</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> * cannot be called either. This file explicitly creates functions (\"helpers\")</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> * that wrap those so that they can be called from Rust.</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> *</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> * Sorted alphabetically.</span>\n<span class=\"cm\"> */</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 531144958,
        "sender_full_name": "Miguel Ojeda",
        "timestamp": 1753624743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, I haven't seen the <code>rust/helpers/helpers.c</code> until now, thanks!</p>",
